A stack adds and removes at the **same end** (the *top*), so the last thing pushed is the first thing popped — last in, first out. That is exactly what Undo needs: it reverses your *most recent* action first.

```js
const history = [];
history.push('edit1');
history.push('edit2');
history.push('edit3');
console.log(history.pop()); // 'edit3'
```

Arrays in JavaScript preserve insertion order, and `pop()` always removes the final element, so the result is deterministic — never random, and never "all at once." Reach for the oldest item first and you've described a *queue* (FIFO), not a stack.

FIFO requires adding and removing at **opposite** ends. `push` appends to the back and `shift` removes from the front, so items leave in the order they arrived:

```js
const queue = [];
queue.push('taskA'); // enqueue
queue.push('taskB');
queue.push('taskC');
console.log(queue.shift()); // 'taskA' — first in, first out
console.log(queue.shift()); // 'taskB'
```

The distractors all act on a **single end**, which makes a *stack* (LIFO): `push`+`pop` both touch the back, `unshift`+`shift` both touch the front, and `pop` removes an element so it can't "enqueue" anything. (`unshift`+`pop` is the *other* valid FIFO pairing — it's just slower, because `unshift` reindexes the whole array on every call.)

The two stacks mirror each other. **Undo** pops the top of `undo` and pushes it onto `redo`; **Redo** pops the top of `redo` and pushes it back onto `undo`. Crucially, redo must be a *stack*, not a queue — otherwise repeated redo replays in the wrong order:

```js
const undo = [], redo = [];
const apply  = (op) => { undo.push(op); redo.length = 0; };
const doUndo = () => { if (undo.length) redo.push(undo.pop()); };
const doRedo = () => { if (redo.length) undo.push(redo.pop()); };

apply('A'); apply('B'); apply('C');
doUndo(); doUndo();      // undo C, then B
console.log(redo);       // [ 'C', 'B' ] — B is on top
doRedo();                // redo pops B first (LIFO)
console.log(undo);       // [ 'A', 'B' ]
console.log(redo);       // [ 'C' ]
```

Because you undid C and then B, redo holds `[C, B]` with **B on top**. The next Redo must replay B before C to retrace your path exactly. A FIFO redo *queue* would replay C first and corrupt the sequence.

This is the most famous undo/redo bug. After undoing, the redo stack holds the "future" you backed out of. A brand-new edit forks a **new branch** of history; the saved redo operations were recorded against a document state you can no longer reach, so replaying them would apply changes to the wrong content and corrupt the document. The fix is one line — every action that is not itself an undo/redo clears redo:

```js
const undo = [];
let redo = [];
const applyEdit = (op) => { undo.push(op); redo = []; }; // <-- clears redo
const undoOnce  = () => { if (undo.length) redo.push(undo.pop()); };

applyEdit('a');
applyEdit('b');
undoOnce();
console.log(redo.length); // 1  (redo available)
applyEdit('X');           // brand-new edit forks a new branch
console.log(redo.length); // 0  (redo correctly discarded)
```

This is why most editors offer only *linear* undo: preserving the redo branch instead would require an **undo tree**, which is much harder to model and to present in a UI.

A bounded history keeps a *sliding window* of the most recent N actions. When full, you discard from the **bottom** (the oldest) and push the new action on **top** — which is why an array-backed stack calls `shift()` to evict before `push()`:

```js
const MAX = 3, undo = [];
const push = (op) => { undo.push(op); if (undo.length > MAX) undo.shift(); };
push('e1'); push('e2'); push('e3'); push('e4');
console.log(undo); // [ 'e2', 'e3', 'e4' ] — oldest 'e1' dropped
```

That makes a bounded stack internally a **deque** (operations at *both* ends) — the same shape as a "recent items" list: newest in at the front, oldest out at the back. The trade-off is real: bounding caps memory but means the oldest edits fall off and can no longer be undone. The false option is backwards — you must never discard the action the user just took in order to keep stale history.

The structure is a **deque** (pronounced "deck"), short for *double-ended queue*. Unlike a stack (one open end) or a plain queue (add at one end, remove at the other), a deque lets you push and pop at *either* end, so it can act as a stack, a queue, or both at once. That flexibility is why it backs a bounded "recent items" list — add the newest to the front, evict the oldest from the back:

```js
const MAX = 3, recent = [];
const visit = (item) => {
  const dup = recent.indexOf(item);
  if (dup !== -1) recent.splice(dup, 1); // de-dupe
  recent.unshift(item);                  // newest to the front
  if (recent.length > MAX) recent.pop(); // evict oldest from the back
};
visit('a'); visit('b'); visit('c'); visit('d');
console.log(recent); // [ 'd', 'c', 'b' ] — 'a' evicted
```

Note that *deque* (the structure) is different from *dequeue* (the queue operation that removes the front element) — they are spelled and pronounced differently.
